<section xml:id="section-activity-clo2">
  <title>Activity for CLO-2</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-clo2-review">
    <title>Conceptual Review</title>
    <p>
      You can test your learning from the video (and your own
      background knowledge) with the following review questions.
      Conceptual questions on quizes may be taken from these review
      questions. 
    </p>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Why are conics called <sq>conics</sq>?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <sq>Conics</sq> is short for <sq>conic sections</sq>, with
          <sq>section</sq> being used archaically to mean a cut or a
          slipe. Conics are slices of cones: they are all the shape
          you can get by slicing a hollow cone at various angles. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Why are conics the most common and approachable type of
          locus after lines?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Lines are loci of linear equations. A linear equation is the
          most simple kind of algebraic equation: it only involves
          variables multiplied by constants and added together. 
        </p>
        <p>
          After a linear equation, the next simplest kind of equation
          is an equation where variables are either squared or
          multiplied by each other once. If <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are
          the variables, then the expressions <m>x^2</m>, <m>y^2</m>
          and <m>xy</m> are allowed in the equation. Introducing these
          terms produces equations whose loci are conics, hence conics
          are the next simplest kind of locus. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What are the four types of conics and what are their
          equations centred at the origin. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <ul>
            <li>
              A circle is a horizontal slice of a cone. It is
              determined by a radius <m>r</m> and the equation,
              centred at the origin, is <m>x^2 + y^2 = r^2</m>.
            </li>
            <li>
              An ellipse is a slice of a cone at a mild angle to the
              horizontal. It is determined by two semi-axes, the
              larger being called the semi-major axis and the smaller
              being called the semi-minor axis. It's equation, centred
              at the origin, is <m>\frac{x^2}{a^2} + \frac{y^2}{b^2} =
              1</m>. 
            </li>
            <li>
              A parabola is a slice of a cone at precisely the angle
              of the cone. Its equation, centred at the origin, is
              <m>y = ax^2</m>. 
            </li>
            <li>
              A hyperbola is a slice of a cone at an angle steeper
              than the angle of the cone. Its equation, centred at the
              origin, is <m>\frac{x^2}{a^2} - \frac{y^2}{b^2} = 1</m>.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is a vertex of a parabola and what is vertex form?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Vertex form is a polynomial written this way. 
          <md>
            y = a(x + b)^2 + c
          </md>
          It is important and useful because the vertex of the
          polynomial is easily identified: the vertex if <m>\left(
          -b, c)</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What does <sq>completing the square</sq> accomplish for a
          parabola? Why does it work?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Completing the square takes a general parabola and writes it
          in vertex form. It works because the squared binomial, when
          expanded, recover the correct linear. When the constant term
          from the square binomial is added to the vertex form constant
          term, this also recovers the original constant from the
          general parabola. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-equations-of-conics">
    <title>Calculation Question: Equations of Conics</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the equation of an ellipse centred at the origin with
          semi-major axis 4 and semi-minor axis 2. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The standard form of the equation of an ellipse centred at
          the origin is <m> \frac{x^2}{a^2} + \frac{y^2}{b^2} = 1</m>
          where <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are the semi-axes in the
          <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> directions, respectively. I've been
          told in the equation that the semi-major axis is 4 and the
          semi-minor axis is 2; but the question didn't specify which
          was the horizontal and which was the vertical directly.
          Therefore, I can just choose: setting <m>a=2</m> and
          <m>b=4</m> or vice-versa. 
          <md>
            \frac{x^2}{4} + \frac{y^2}{16} = 1 \text{ or }
            \frac{x^2}{16} + \frac{y^2}{4} = 1 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the equation of the circle centred at the origin with
          radius <m>\sqrt{15}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The standard form of the equation of an circle centred at
          the origin is <m>x^2 + y^2 = r^2</m>. I am given the
          radius of <m>\sqrt{15}</m>, so I just square that value in
          insert it into the equation.
          <md>
            x^2 + y^2 = 15
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write the equation of the parabola with vertex <m>(3,-2)</m>
          and leading coefficient <m>\frac{1}{4}</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The standard form of the equation of a parabola with vertex
          <m>(a,b)</m> and leading coefficient <m>c</m> is <m>y = c (x
          - a)^2 + b </m>. I can just replace the three unknown with
          what I am given in the problem.
          <md>
            y = \frac{1}{4} (x-3)^2 - 2 
          </md>
          If I want a more conventional equation for this parabola,
          I can expand.
          <md>
            y = \frac{1}{4} (x^2 - 6x + 9) - 2 = \frac{1}{4} x^2 -
            \frac{3}{2} x + \frac{1}{4} 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Write this polynomial in vertex form. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I start by completing the square. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
</section>
